comment:
zohran. offers. positive. change. for. working. people.

it's really that simple. how the dnc doesn't see this is beyond me? the pollution and outright corruption, the influence of wall street (private equity, billionaire) money on both parties has brought us to where we are.

do people not remember what it was like for our grandparents? our grandfathers bought homes on one salary. they both went to college on gi bills. 

one raised 5 kids, all in private school. the other raised 2, both in private school. they took vacations. could afford to stock the pantry and have money left for restaurants and travel, investments.

these were not wealthy men. just ordinary guys who received generous help from fellow humanity (i.e, the government) got lucky and excelled.

both worked careers. one job for 30ish years. a pension and ss waiting for them. 

what changed? unmitigated greed. 

wall street and the political donor class were allowed to run wild. the abyss opened in the 1980s under reagan. the rot grew under clinton and bush 43 (i.e. cheney) made it infinitely worse. 

obama succombed to wall street, as well, and abandoned his promises. trying to play civil politics with the liars and cheaters in the gop.

trump is trump. an empty vessel for literal confederate insurrectionists and traitors to the constitution. attracting the absolute worst of the worst in the billionaire milieu.

our grandparents lived under "extreme" left policies of the new deal. companies like levitt & sons building prefab "levittowns". affordable housing en masse. of course they didn't have to deal with nimbys and a pequity complex _(now outnumbering the number of mcdonald's in the us)._

i don't understand working people who vote against their own interests. people who blithely buy into the same willie horton fear mongering propaganda which conservative think tanks and their billionaire donor class masters use to divide working people with phony, contrived episodes of "otherism".

we even had state colleges that were almost effectively free of charge during the 40s-70s. 

we can't all be millionaires. it simply cannot be. yet someone needs to drive the bus, clean the toilet, deliver packages, wait tables, and cook our meals.

they all, we all, deserve dignity. the possibility of a comfortable retirement not dependent on chance or fluctuating markets. stability and peace of mind.

i wish conservatives would come for tours of some areas that have been abandoned by capital. the places that used to be filled with homeowners and workers are now filled with renters. see some of the realities of american poverty and how it stretches beyond generations.

comment:
it's weird the criticism / dismissal of steve bannon by you two - he is one of the only people who's correctly diagnosed and presented a framework to understand politics, since 2015. 

to boil it down to it's most basic level, it's now the populist left, verses the populist right. 

what resonates with we the people more than anything else, is being able to correctly identify the problems, in a very clear and transparent way. in a way that concedes that even leaders on your own side of the political aisle contributed to all the problems we are looking at today.

this is why trump was so popular in 2015 and 2016, because he did exactly that. he had his finger on the pulse of what actually were all the problems, and he didn't have a problem throwing accusations at even his own side on the things they did to contribute, because it was true, and it's been a long bubbling rage building on both the left and the right for a long time....that the establishment on the left and the right is why we are here today. they continued contributing to the problems, making them worse, all while denying they were even real problems. 

this is also why bernie sanders was so popular, and why bannon has respect for him. bannon is a political strategist at heart, and he fully recognizes the value that being able to correctly identify the problems that the american people face has - he just believes that it's the populist right that has the correct remedies to those problems. 

but he fully recognizes that when it comes to connecting with the people, and getting grassroots support, being able to identify what the problem is, is 80% of the battle. and the populist left, even if their solutions are terrible and will make things worse, will be able to win elections if they stick to their populist principles, and don't get co-opted by the establishment. 

and that's where mamdani comes in - he's a populist. young people look at him and see someone who is able to articulate what the problems are very clearly. and while his solutions would only make things worse, that's not something that most people even look to with any depth - just finding someone that is able to speak to what average americans are dealing with today is going to resonate and connect with them like nothing else will. 

and that's why bannon respects people like mamdani - he's effectively capturing the populist left, by seeing the world how it is. his solutions may be terrible, bannon likely disagrees with every single one of his solutions, but bannon respects the game. if mamdani is able to do the leg work to connect with more people in new york and gain their support by speaking truth to their struggles, then he has earned the win. 

doesn't mean bannon thinks it's going to lead to some prosperous new york or other such nonsense, but this is about political strategy. and anyone that sees how the political landscape has changed drastically since 2015, to recognize that it's now about populism rather than establishment politics, bannon will have respect for that.

comment:
in terms of why polling underestimated mamdani's turnout: i think it is because polls rely on people that are regular voters, or at least are in some voter database somewhere, but mamdani galvanized folks that had either never voted before, or were low-propensity voters for the recent past at least. i keep thinking about the south asian indian/pakistani/bengali neighborhoods of jackson heights as a case study. many folks there are likely low-propensity voters, but they, like many others, saw themselves in mamdani and came out to vote, but many of them are likely not well-captured in any polling data due to their voting history.

polls are just a mathematical way to incorporate the assumptions of a pollster. at some level, they assign numeric weights to their assumptions. this became very clear in this race.
